'''Town supervisor''' is an elective [[Legislature|legislative]] position in [[New York (state)|New York]] [[Administrative divisions of New York#Town|towns]].<ref name="LGHsupervisor">{{cite web|url=https://www.dos.ny.gov/lg/publications/Local_Government_Handbook.pdf|title=Local Government Handbook|pages=PDF page 66|format=PDF|publisher=New York State Department of State|year=2009|edition=6th|accessdate=January 15, 2017}}</ref> Supervisors sit on the [[Town council|town board]], where they preside over town board meetings and vote on all matters with no more legal weight than that of any other board member (no tie-breaking or [[veto]] powers).
Towns may adopt local laws that allow them to provide for an [[Executive (government)|executive]] branch, an action authorized by the [[New York State Legislature]].<ref name="LGHsupervisor"/> As such, some supervisors have additional authority or executive powers, whereas some towns have town managers or chief executive officers who serve as the executive branch, leaving the supervisor to his or her traditional role in the legislative branch.<ref name="LGHsupervisor"/>
In most towns the supervisor is considered a [[full time|full-time]] position, although many supervisors also have other jobs concurrently, while the service on the town board is considered [[part time|part-time]] work.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}
